{
  "texts": [
    "The third step is model application, meaning that the trained model is applied to specific cases or individuals, making the model a tool that computes a specific output in response to input data (Mühlhoff & Ruschemeier, 2024b).",
    "This quantity of data and the training process mean model output contains information about cases or individuals as well as that of \"third parties\" that were not part of the training data.",
    "The first problem area relates to how the training of powerful AI models, or the processing of large amounts of data, works in relation to the amount of data processed (Zarsky, 2017).",
    "The sheer quantity of data processed by potent AI models is the core, as yet unresolved, problem of AI and data protection.",
    "11 Generative AI models are typically trained on billions, if not hundreds of billions, of parameters and require large amounts of training data and computing power (Brown et al., 2020)."
  ]
}